The MA seminar is structured in four parts covering four semesters. The first part consists of seminars training students for basic study and research skills (including how to approach your research topic, how to find relevant literature, how to read research literature, how to present your work in written and oral form, how to find and apply for conferences on your topic, etc.). The second part is more specifically aimed at training presentation and question&answer skills. In the third and fourth part students present their work in progress and give feedback to their peers. During the two semesters, specific seminars are held to provide professional insight and practical help with PhD and non-academic options after MA studies.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The central aim is to develop a set of skills required for both successful Master's studies and for future academic and non-academic professional work. As it proceeds to the second part, the MA seminar is also a forum to present and discuss one's work in progress with peers and teachers in charge.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  On successful completion of the course a student - has practiced crucial skills for successful MA studies, such as essay writing skills - has practiced crucial skills for successful research, such as defining a research problem, looking for relevant sources, etc. - has practiced presentation skills and question&answer routine - has learned how to write an abstract and a handout - can provide feedback on the work of others - has sufficient knowledge of academic and non-academic work options after MA studies - is in a position to apply to PhD programs in philosophy or related disciplines
